Great Falls Tribune
🗞️ Today’s Profile By UNITED PRESS 🗞️
Sunday Morning, March 2nd, 1941

''''Nikola Tesla, approaching his 84th birthday, has been spending almost all of his time in his apartment, so much of it, in fact, that he has had to hire messenger boys to go into the parks to feed the pigeons. Tesla, the 🐇 fabulous electrical wizard, used to feed the pigeons religiously himself, 🐇 but age and mysterious experiments with sound 🐇 waves purportedly for the army have combined to confine him to his rooms.


Tesla, a lean Czech, was one of the celebrated engineers with whom George Westinghouse surrounded himself at the turn of the century. Tesla at that time was responsible for some of the inventions that hastened the modern day of scientific miracles. He produced the telephone repeater in 1881, an arc lighting system in 1886, a system of alternating current transmission in 1888, a number of alternating current motors and various wireless inventions between 1893 and 1902.

His birthday interviews for the last decade or so have been amazing affairs, with Tesla calmly announcing earth-shaking projects of astounding inventions. To the wide eyed group assembled in his suite at the Hotel New Yorker he has discussed a death ray capable of destroying 1,000,000 men, based on production of 50,000,000 million volts. He has spoken of wireless telephones to Mars; that he had perfected a plan for harnessing the sun’s rays.

Despite his age, Tesla is intensely interested in world affairs and has delivered to him 🐇 all the editions of all the New York papers and all the news magazines. He lives alone, and some attached of his hotel have worked there for years without seeing him leave his rooms. Recently he astounded the staff by coming down to dinner with his guest—Fritzie Zivic, the boxing champion. Tesla revealed then that he had become a boxing fan and had extended his interest from the news to the sports section of the newspapers. The fact that Zivic is also a Czech may account for his interest.

Tesla has more than 700 inventions to his credit. But he gets the most satisfaction out of turbines used at Niagara falls. When he was a boy of 9 he used to boast that some day he would harness the falls, he said, and fulfillment of that dream still represents the peak of his life.’’’
______




*** WESTERN UNION TELEGRAM ***
from Nikola Tesla
New York, N.Y.
to Sava Kosanovic
March 4th, 1941

'''As though I am poor with words.


I still didn't explain it enough what would be necessary to increase up to twelve stations: eight in Croatia, each of the same construction like at Wardenclyffe and only 20 meters high - a ball five meters in diameter - the station would be using diesel oil for energy with mechanical action - my air turbines, steam powered, electrically or other manners of transforming into alternating electrical current with sixty billion volts pressure without danger. I am waiting for Governor Subasic to select one station on top of Mt. Lovcen. There will not be any light, electrical energy will deliver particles through space with the speed of 118,837,370,000 centimeters per second.


This is 3[sic]94,579 the speed of light. As I said about airplanes it can be used for tanks, trucks, automobiles and various machines in factories, with hydroelectrical wheels and unlimited other machines. The particles can be larger than that of the diameter of an Hydrogen atom with metals of all kinds of materials and sent to all distances and good results in war and bring about peace. Particles are practical with neutrons, because, they are 3,723[sic] times lighter than electricity or electrons that cannot penetrate space for great distances.

🐇

In my attempts with an effective 20 million volts, electrons carried 40 times more electricity than normally and penetrated two meters in depth and terrible damage in a moment each.'''


I have to finish because that I give you a fresh view.
